00:00:50.530 --> 00:00:53.830
is this book.

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:56.770
Now, eight years ago,
I gave a talk at Google

00:00:56.770 --> 00:01:00.760
on soaring cryptography
and nuclear weapons.

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:04.150
I always like to do things that
kind of get people wondering.

00:01:04.150 --> 00:01:07.900
And my work then-- and
it still continues--

00:01:07.900 --> 00:01:11.710
has been on bringing
risk analysis to bear

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:13.370
on the question of
nuclear deterrence.

00:01:13.370 --> 00:01:16.210
How risky is it to threaten
to destroy civilization

00:01:16.210 --> 00:01:18.190
in an effort to
preserve the peace?

00:01:18.190 --> 00:01:21.790
Well, my research has convinced
me it's a horrendous risk,

00:01:21.790 --> 00:01:25.330
and that talk weight out
why, and this book also

00:01:25.330 --> 00:01:26.950
helps to explain that.

00:01:26.950 --> 00:01:30.040
But even though that talk--

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:33.040
you put it on YouTube--
got roughly 10,000 views--

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:36.460
which is quite a lot
for an hour-long talk--

00:01:36.460 --> 00:01:39.220
almost no one is interested
in nuclear weapons.

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:41.740
Almost no one is interested
in war and peace,

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:45.080
even though their lives depend
on it, and they don't know it.

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:47.620
And so about three years
ago, Dorothie and I

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:51.020
decided that we were going to
take a new approach-- actually

00:01:51.020 --> 00:01:52.060
it's an old approach.

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:54.670
Because 35 years ago
when I shifted my work

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:59.410
from information security to
international security, what

00:01:59.410 --> 00:02:03.640
got both of us interested in
this international security

00:02:03.640 --> 00:02:06.180
wasn't wanting to save
the world initially,

00:02:06.180 --> 00:02:09.149
it was wanting to
save our marriage.

00:02:09.149 --> 00:02:11.440
Now by the way, we just
celebrated our 50th anniversary

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:12.483
on Friday.

00:02:12.483 --> 00:02:14.798
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:18.210
But we almost didn't make it.

00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:21.210
Not in recent years, but
35 years ago, the marriage

00:02:21.210 --> 00:02:22.154
was in some trouble.

00:02:22.154 --> 00:02:23.820
And I was so busy I
didn't even know it,

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:25.950
but Dorothie fortunately
was watching out

00:02:25.950 --> 00:02:29.610
and started a process that
we talk about in the book,

00:02:29.610 --> 00:02:32.740
and we'll talk about today.

00:02:32.740 --> 00:02:36.210
And so many more people
are interested in improving

00:02:36.210 --> 00:02:38.730
their relationships than
are interested in improving

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:41.310
international relationships or
dealing with nuclear weapons.

00:02:41.310 --> 00:02:43.470
But as we explain in this
talk, and as the book

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:47.430
explains in more detail, the
two are intimately connected.

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:49.830
And so that's why
our books subtitle

00:02:49.830 --> 00:02:55.110
is "Creating True Love at
Home and Peace on the Planet".

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:58.800
Now, unless you're very unusual,
you sometimes have painful

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:04.800
disagreements with a
spouse, a partner, in-laws--

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:07.260
they'll come up in this talk--

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:08.620
co-workers.

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:12.964
And how would you like to never
be in that kind of pain again?

00:03:12.964 --> 00:03:14.130
Think about it for a minute.

00:03:14.130 --> 00:03:16.740
Never be in that pain again.

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:21.450
Well, this talk will outline
how you can accomplish that.

00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:23.940
And it describes how
we accomplish that

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:27.270
at least in our marriage.

00:03:27.270 --> 00:03:30.530
And it also will show
how doing that allowed

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:33.240
us to make a much larger
contribution to world peace

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:36.400
than we ever would
have thought possible.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.690
So the theme of this talk--
we had to narrow it down

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:40.440
to one sentence.

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:41.280
Here it is.

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:44.880
Your learning to compassionately
resolve personal conflicts

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:50.430
will help determine whether
or not civilization survives.

00:03:50.430 --> 00:03:51.000
That's big.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:51.900
Think about it.

00:03:51.900 --> 00:03:54.180
Your impact can be that big.

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:55.690
Plus, you'll be happier.

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:58.980
Now, this is a short talk
and would take a whole book

00:03:58.980 --> 00:03:59.972
to explain that.

00:03:59.972 --> 00:04:01.680
But fortunately, we've
written that book,

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:04.710
and Google very generously
bought a bunch from Books Inc.

00:04:04.710 --> 00:04:08.397
and has made them
available to people here.

00:04:08.397 --> 00:04:10.980
And at the end of the talk, I'll
mention how everyone else can

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:12.780
get a free copy of the book.

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:14.940
But I'll leave that for then.

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:18.899
So where does the title, "A
New Map for Relationships"

00:04:18.899 --> 00:04:19.440
come from?

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:20.730
That's the main title.

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:23.310
Well, the first story in
the book is all about that,

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:26.160
and Dorothie is the
star of that story,

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:28.110
so she's going to tell you.

00:04:28.110 --> 00:04:33.350
DOROTHIE HELLMAN: We were going
to San Francisco to an event.

00:04:33.350 --> 00:04:36.780
It was a Friday afternoon.

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:38.470
The sun was shining
in San Francisco,

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:39.930
and it was just beautiful.

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:41.940
So we thought we'd
drive up to Twin Peaks

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:44.760
and enjoy the
beauty of the city.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:47.940
And we were sitting in the
car getting ready to go,

00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:49.350
and I pulled out the map.

00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:50.520
It was a paper map.

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:51.720
It was that long ago.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:53.760
MARTIN HELLMAN: No Google Maps.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:55.230
DOROTHIE HELLMAN:
And I was trying

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:57.479
to figure out how we were
going to get from Twin Peaks

00:04:57.479 --> 00:04:59.190
to our event.

00:04:59.190 --> 00:05:05.800
And Marty, without asking,
took the map out of my hands.

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:09.780
And one of my pet peeves
was him doing that.

00:05:09.780 --> 00:05:11.890
He knew it would bother me.

00:05:11.890 --> 00:05:13.260
So I was furious.

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:15.540
And so I got out of the
door, and I slammed the door,

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:17.700
and I got out of the
car, and I huffed off.

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:20.700
And I was just sitting there
like, I couldn't believe

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:21.701
he did that to me again.

00:05:21.701 --> 00:05:23.408
MARTIN HELLMAN: And
of course, I actually

00:05:23.408 --> 00:05:25.170
had forgotten that
that was her pet peeve,

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:26.500
or I wouldn't have done it.

00:05:26.500 --> 00:05:28.680
But I actually didn't know
what I had done at first.

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:31.600
And so I was sitting in the
car wondering what to do.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:34.860
I have to admit, I was
tempted to drive off.

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:37.050
She'd stomped off like
she was never coming back.

00:05:37.050 --> 00:05:38.610
I should drive off.

00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:42.894
It felt really stupid to just
sit there waiting for her.

00:05:42.894 --> 00:05:44.310
It felt like she
was the princess,

00:05:44.310 --> 00:05:47.730
and she would calm down, and
I was literally her attendant

00:05:47.730 --> 00:05:48.810
in waiting.

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:51.990
And when she came to her senses,
I would drive her someplace.

00:05:51.990 --> 00:05:54.690
But fortunately, I
did not drive off.

00:05:54.690 --> 00:05:57.580
DOROTHIE HELLMAN: So
that was very fortunate.

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:01.920
So I got back in the car,
and Marty's reading the map

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:03.130
like this.

00:06:03.130 --> 00:06:06.210
He's ignoring me and
pretending like I'm not there.

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:08.340
So this makes me even madder.

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:10.060
So now I'm really furious.

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:14.870
So without thinking about it,
actually I grab the map out

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:17.450
of Marty's hands, and
I start shredding it.

00:06:17.450 --> 00:06:19.130
I'm tearing it
into little pieces,

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:21.610
and I'm throwing it
all over the car.

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:26.720
And Marty's looking at me like,
I don't know what to do next.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:28.970
But luckily, he
started laughing.

00:06:28.970 --> 00:06:32.240
So he's laughing hysterically,
I'm shredding the map,

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:35.630
and then I start
laughing hysterically.

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:39.320
So then at that point
what we need to do

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:41.330
is we need to take all
the pieces of the map

00:06:41.330 --> 00:06:45.620
and put it back together so
we can figure out where to go.

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:47.390
So you can see
just a little shift

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:52.700
like that, Marty deciding to
laugh instead of get deeper

00:06:52.700 --> 00:06:59.370
in the garbage of our silly
argument, changed everything.

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:02.330
So just a small shift can
change everything, and that's

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:04.340
the power of compassion,
which we're really

00:07:04.340 --> 00:07:06.980
talking about today.

00:07:06.980 --> 00:07:09.320
And as we wrote our
book, we realized

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:17.720
that this tearing up the map was
a metaphor for the whole book,

00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:24.820
that we each brought unconscious
maps to our relationship,

00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:27.970
and it kept helping
us drive off cliffs.

00:07:27.970 --> 00:07:29.890
And that it was scary
to leave the old map,

00:07:29.890 --> 00:07:32.890
because we knew that
map, but we decided

00:07:32.890 --> 00:07:35.350
we weren't going to
keep driving off cliffs,

00:07:35.350 --> 00:07:40.469
so we had to stop and make new
maps and go new directions.

00:07:40.469 --> 00:07:42.010
MARTIN HELLMAN: It's
amazing how much

00:07:42.010 --> 00:07:44.170
we like holding
onto those old maps,

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:47.080
even though they keep
taking us bad places.

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:49.180
And the same is true
internationally.

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:52.360
And in this talk, we have time
for just one piece of evidence,

00:07:52.360 --> 00:07:55.870
and that will be the United
States national security.

00:07:55.870 --> 00:07:58.690
In 1945, at the end
of World War II,

00:07:58.690 --> 00:08:00.550
we had not been touched
by the devastation.

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:02.800
Europe had been devastated,
but the United States

00:08:02.800 --> 00:08:06.100
had been inviolate during
World War II, our homeland.

00:08:06.100 --> 00:08:08.350
And in the intervening
72 years, we've

00:08:08.350 --> 00:08:11.500
spent literally trillions
upon trillions of dollars

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:13.750
to improve our
national security.

00:08:13.750 --> 00:08:16.420
We've put some of our best
minds to work to maximize

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:18.160
the value of that investment.

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:21.130
And let's look at where
the old map has taken us.

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:23.710
1945, we could not be touched.

00:08:23.710 --> 00:08:28.030
2017, we can be destroyed
in under an hour by Russia,

00:08:28.030 --> 00:08:31.912
by China, and if North Korea
keeps doing what it's doing

00:08:31.912 --> 00:08:34.120
and we keep doing what we're
doing with North Korea--

00:08:34.120 --> 00:08:37.390
which I'll get to in
about 10 minutes--

00:08:37.390 --> 00:08:40.330
North Korea might be able
to take out San Francisco.

00:08:40.330 --> 00:08:42.730
Maybe the old map is
not working so well

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:46.160
internationally as well.

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:48.100
DOROTHIE HELLMAN: So
the first key step

00:08:48.100 --> 00:08:51.520
is to believe that peace is
possible, internationally

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:53.170
and personally.

00:08:53.170 --> 00:08:56.575
If we don't believe that peace
is possible, it won't happen.

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:05.020
And if it never happens, society
will never see it happen,

00:09:05.020 --> 00:09:07.900
and we'll just never get there.

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:10.600
Changes in society
depend on just a few

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:14.410
courageous individuals
making shifts

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:18.640
when societal beliefs
are mistaken or wrong

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:22.610
or misunderstood.

00:09:22.610 --> 00:09:31.160
My grandmother was born around
1900 and when she was born,

00:09:31.160 --> 00:09:34.420
women were not allowed to
vote in the United States.

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:38.480
Now, because of that, I've
never missed an election.

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:43.770
And if the suffragettes hadn't
done something around 1900,

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:45.890
I still might not
be able to vote.

00:09:48.600 --> 00:09:50.200
Mark Twain said it very well.

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:52.930
He said, they didn't know it
was impossible, so they did it.

00:09:55.530 --> 00:09:58.880
Marty and I know that
peace is possible,

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:02.180
because we transformed
a 35-year-old--

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:09.080
because we transformed a
turbulent marriage that

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:11.900
was almost on the
rocks 35 years ago

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:15.070
into one where we haven't
had an argument in 15 years.

00:10:17.740 --> 00:10:21.930
A marriage like that seemed
impossible from where

00:10:21.930 --> 00:10:25.170
we stood there, just as
many people now believe

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:28.200
that world peace is impossible.

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:30.330
The lessons we had to
learn in our marriage

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:35.280
were the same lessons we have
to learn internationally.

00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:37.320
If we keep getting
into wars, one of them

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:39.420
will escalate into
nuclear threats,

00:10:39.420 --> 00:10:42.030
and therefore into nuclear war.

00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:44.280
We just can't afford it.

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:46.410
That's why the key
takeaway from this talk

00:10:46.410 --> 00:10:49.770
is Your Learning to
Compassionately Resolve

00:10:49.770 --> 00:10:53.790
Personal Conflicts Will Help
Determine Whether Civilization

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:55.560
Survives.

00:10:55.560 --> 00:10:57.150
I hope you're
starting to see why

00:10:57.150 --> 00:10:59.371
this is not an overstatement.

00:10:59.371 --> 00:11:01.120
MARTIN HELLMAN: Well,
even though it's not

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:04.325
an overstatement, many people
have told me-- actually,

00:11:04.325 --> 00:11:05.950
several people have
told me before they

00:11:05.950 --> 00:11:07.720
read the book they
were very skeptical,

00:11:07.720 --> 00:11:10.210
but after reading it,
we'd made a good case.

00:11:10.210 --> 00:11:13.600
Since most of you have
not read the book,

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:17.620
I'm going to give you two
appraisals of the book that

00:11:17.620 --> 00:11:19.480
come from authoritative
individuals that

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:22.240
help to deal with this question
of how creating true love home

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:26.020
actually carries over to
creating peace on the planet.

00:11:26.020 --> 00:11:29.602
The first is a former Secretary
of Defense, Bill Perry.

00:11:29.602 --> 00:11:31.310
He's a colleague of
mine at Stanford now.

00:11:31.310 --> 00:11:34.160
He was Secretary of
Defense under Bill Clinton.

00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:37.990
And he calls the book truly
unique, and recommends quote,

00:11:37.990 --> 00:11:40.600
"That it should be read by
couples seeking peace at home

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:44.650
as well as by diplomats
seeking peace in the world."

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:48.310
Karl Eikenberry, who
was a three-star general

00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:50.440
in Afghanistan, led
the coalition troops,

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:53.200
and then later under President
Obama was our ambassador

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:55.360
to Afghanistan--

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:57.880
also now a colleague of mine
at Stanford-- read the book

00:11:57.880 --> 00:12:00.310
and calls it quote, "The
most thoughtful, unique,

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:02.140
and fascinating
book I've ever read

00:12:02.140 --> 00:12:05.260
on personal and
international diplomacy."

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:07.690
So skepticism is
understandable, but I

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:11.100
hope quotes like that will help
you get over the skepticism,

00:12:11.100 --> 00:12:12.850
or at least get you
to read it on your own

00:12:12.850 --> 00:12:15.424
and form your own opinion.

00:12:15.424 --> 00:12:17.590
I'm just going to move these
over just a little bit.

00:12:17.590 --> 00:12:20.800
Now, how we respond to
conflict at the personal level

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:24.760
determines how we
as a nation respond

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:28.450
to conflict on the
international stage.

00:12:28.450 --> 00:12:32.200
How can anyone be at
war with their spouse,

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:35.350
with colleagues at work,
and say with a straight face

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:37.840
that peace is
possible in the world?

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:40.650
It just doesn't work.

00:12:40.650 --> 00:12:44.540
It's much easier to
call for world peace--

00:12:44.540 --> 00:12:46.100
I want world peace--

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:49.009
than it is to create
peace at home.

00:12:49.009 --> 00:12:50.550
I know that from
personal experience.

00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:52.470
It's also the most
rewarding thing I ever did,

00:12:52.470 --> 00:12:54.950
so it was worth
all that hard work.

00:12:54.950 --> 00:12:58.100
For anyone who wants
to improve the world,

00:12:58.100 --> 00:13:01.160
personal relationships
are the testing ground

00:13:01.160 --> 00:13:04.130
for that larger vision.

00:13:04.130 --> 00:13:08.270
Conversely, because we have
transformed our marriage from--

00:13:08.270 --> 00:13:10.580
I sometimes say we
fought all the time,

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:13.160
and Dorothie would object.

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:16.070
So we changed it,
frequent fights.

00:13:16.070 --> 00:13:17.360
Is that OK?

00:13:17.360 --> 00:13:20.600
Frequent fights, to one where
as Dorothie has pointed out,

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:22.456
fights are now a
nightmare of the past.

00:13:22.456 --> 00:13:23.830
I didn't think
that was possible,

00:13:23.830 --> 00:13:26.930
and I have to give her full
credit for that vision,

00:13:26.930 --> 00:13:28.970
and of dragging me
through this process,

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:30.330
at times kicking and screaming.

00:13:30.330 --> 00:13:32.300
And now I'm really grateful.

00:13:32.300 --> 00:13:37.000
I didn't think a marriage where
you don't fight was possible.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.046
We still disagree, by the
way, about a lot of things.

00:13:40.046 --> 00:13:42.170
We learn a lot from each
other because we disagree.

00:13:42.170 --> 00:13:43.545
But what's the
point in fighting?

00:13:43.545 --> 00:13:46.280
When did yelling at her
ever get me what I wanted?

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:48.530
And yet in the old map,
that's what I kept doing.

00:13:48.530 --> 00:13:52.010
That's one of the cliffs
that we kept driving off.

00:13:52.010 --> 00:13:54.680
Our marriage became a laboratory
in which we carried out

00:13:54.680 --> 00:13:57.200
repeated experiments
for learning

00:13:57.200 --> 00:13:59.730
how adversaries might
solve what appear

00:13:59.730 --> 00:14:03.400
to be insoluble conflicts.

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:08.610
So having achieved true peace
in what had been an extremely

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:12.150
turbulent marriage, we
can say with conviction

00:14:12.150 --> 00:14:14.760
that peace is possible
at the world level,

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:19.805
because we as Dorothie said,
it was inconceivable to us--

00:14:19.805 --> 00:14:21.180
or at least to
me-- that we could

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:23.250
have this kind of
relationship, just as it's

00:14:23.250 --> 00:14:25.590
inconceivable to
most people today

00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:28.440
that we could have peace
at the world of level.

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:30.630
They didn't know it was
impossible, so they did it.

00:14:34.160 --> 00:14:37.324
So now, you're going to
tell them about my parents.

00:14:37.324 --> 00:14:39.740
DOROTHIE HELLMAN: I'm going
to tell a story about how just

00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:41.690
one person can make a shift.

00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:44.680
There's always the
question, OK, if there are

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:45.930
two of you working, it's good.

00:14:45.930 --> 00:14:48.200
But how about if
there's only one?

00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:50.415
Well, I'm going to tell you
a story about my in-laws.

00:14:53.570 --> 00:14:55.970
Marty comes from a Jewish
family, and I don't.

00:14:55.970 --> 00:14:59.330
And his parents
were very concerned

00:14:59.330 --> 00:15:02.540
about him marrying
outside the faith.

00:15:02.540 --> 00:15:05.040
So I know I had this problem.

00:15:05.040 --> 00:15:11.000
So when I met his parents,
they were pretty nice to me.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.110
But the day after
I met his father,

00:15:15.110 --> 00:15:17.360
we were talking in
the kitchen, and he

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:21.650
said, Dorothie, you
remind me of my mother.

00:15:21.650 --> 00:15:24.050
And I said, why,
thank you very much.

00:15:24.050 --> 00:15:27.050
And he said, I never
liked my mother.

00:15:27.050 --> 00:15:28.070
We didn't get along.

00:15:31.430 --> 00:15:34.430
So now I've got a problem.

00:15:34.430 --> 00:15:38.180
So this continued, and
it was so painful for me

00:15:38.180 --> 00:15:40.800
that I tried different things.

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:48.540
I tried taking Valium,
that didn't work.

00:15:48.540 --> 00:15:50.290
Somebody at one of
these talks suggested

00:15:50.290 --> 00:15:56.290
that I should have given them
Valium, that didn't work.

00:15:56.290 --> 00:15:58.810
So eventually I
stopped going, just

00:15:58.810 --> 00:16:02.050
because it wrecked the whole--

00:16:02.050 --> 00:16:06.190
my children should have a good
visit with their grandchildren.

00:16:09.960 --> 00:16:15.200
So what I decided
to do was I decided

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:17.500
to go with total compassion.

00:16:17.500 --> 00:16:19.730
And I was going to
visit, and my whole goal

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:21.890
was to make them feel loved.

00:16:21.890 --> 00:16:24.830
And nothing they said had
anything to do with me.

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:27.090
It was totally irrelevant.

00:16:27.090 --> 00:16:29.160
And it totally worked.

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:31.950
They felt totally loved by me.

00:16:31.950 --> 00:16:34.770
They felt that I made
this huge change,

00:16:34.770 --> 00:16:39.900
and they felt that all the
problems in our relationship

00:16:39.900 --> 00:16:42.260
had shifted.

00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:45.020
And even the Jewish
part went away.

00:16:45.020 --> 00:16:47.870
So compassion is a power tool.

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:50.000
That's what I'd say about that.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.040
And if you think about
it, in the old map,

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:55.380
Dorothie taking
full responsibility

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:57.420
and not worrying about
what my parents said

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:01.080
and deciding that the visit was
a success if my parents felt

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:03.960
loved by her no matter
what they said or did,

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:06.750
she'd be seen as a
wimp in the old map.

00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:08.579
And yet you can see
from the results

00:17:08.579 --> 00:17:09.810
that she was far from a wimp.

00:17:09.810 --> 00:17:12.119
Compassion gave her
tremendous power.

00:17:12.119 --> 00:17:14.740
So the old map and the new map
are really totally different,

00:17:14.740 --> 00:17:16.781
and it's hard to understand
the new map until you

00:17:16.781 --> 00:17:18.119
start experimenting with it.

00:17:18.119 --> 00:17:19.859
I know that was true for me.

00:17:19.859 --> 00:17:22.800
I now do things that would
have seemed crazy to me

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:27.530
35 years ago, and they
work out wonderfully.

00:17:27.530 --> 00:17:29.530
So what about
internationally, though?

00:17:29.530 --> 00:17:31.810
OK, we've just seen
how sometimes it

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:34.775
only takes one party to
a conflict to resolve

00:17:34.775 --> 00:17:35.650
an interpersonal one.

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:37.330
But what about internationally?

00:17:37.330 --> 00:17:40.180
How can the United
States resolve

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:46.210
the conflict we have with
nations like North Korea, Iran,

00:17:46.210 --> 00:17:47.260
Russia?

00:17:47.260 --> 00:17:49.030
I mean, those seem impossible.

00:17:49.030 --> 00:17:50.770
They have to change, don't they?

00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:58.690
Well, in the book we have seven
international case studies,

00:17:58.690 --> 00:17:59.989
including those three nations.

00:17:59.989 --> 00:18:02.030
There are four other
nations that are dealt with.

00:18:02.030 --> 00:18:03.731
In this talk, we just
have time for one.

00:18:03.731 --> 00:18:05.230
So I'm going to
take what's probably

00:18:05.230 --> 00:18:07.120
the hardest one, North Korea.

00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:17.170
North Korea probably wouldn't
have any nuclear weapons today

00:18:17.170 --> 00:18:20.320
if President Bush hadn't
torn up a nuclear agreement

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:24.020
that we had with them in 2002.

00:18:24.020 --> 00:18:26.660
That agreement kept them
from extracting plutonium.

00:18:26.660 --> 00:18:28.370
It protected their
plutonium stockpile.

00:18:28.370 --> 00:18:30.036
It was under international
lock and key.

00:18:30.036 --> 00:18:33.290
When he tore it up, they
kicked the inspectors out,

00:18:33.290 --> 00:18:35.720
and they started
extracting plutonium.

00:18:35.720 --> 00:18:38.570
And four years later,
they did their first test.

00:18:38.570 --> 00:18:42.137
Now, this is so contrary to
what you read in the media,

00:18:42.137 --> 00:18:43.970
that when you read that
section of the book,

00:18:43.970 --> 00:18:46.700
you notice lots of
little numbered endnotes.

00:18:46.700 --> 00:18:48.450
They were kind of
unobtrusive that way.

00:18:48.450 --> 00:18:51.260
But if you want to see the
source documents that back this

00:18:51.260 --> 00:18:54.440
up, you go to the end of the
book, and you can find them.

00:18:54.440 --> 00:18:59.720
And in fact, if you go online to
the book's website anewmap.com

00:18:59.720 --> 00:19:02.000
and then you add slash
notes, all of those notes

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:06.170
are repeated online
with clickable links

00:19:06.170 --> 00:19:07.190
where appropriate.

00:19:07.190 --> 00:19:09.830
And so if you want to see some
of these top secret Documents

00:19:09.830 --> 00:19:12.380
with the top secret crossed
out, now declassified,

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:13.790
you can see that.

00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:18.460
But in this talk, I'll
just mention something

00:19:18.460 --> 00:19:20.640
as backup for that statement.

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:24.260
I'll read from a paper written
by a former director of Los

00:19:24.260 --> 00:19:27.290
Alamos Nuclear
Weapons Laboratory.

00:19:27.290 --> 00:19:29.190
Not a peacenik.

00:19:29.190 --> 00:19:32.180
He's now a colleague of
mine, Dr. Siegfried Hecker.

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:35.360
And he's visited North
Korea seven times

00:19:35.360 --> 00:19:37.820
on what are known as track
two diplomatic missions.

00:19:37.820 --> 00:19:40.380
So he has firsthand
information on this country,

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:43.530
as well as knowing nuclear
weapons really well.

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:45.110
In fact, the joke
about Sieg is he

00:19:45.110 --> 00:19:49.370
hasn't met a phase of
plutonium he doesn't like.

00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:51.170
He's a chemical
engineer by training,

00:19:51.170 --> 00:19:52.700
and plutonium is his specialty.

00:19:52.700 --> 00:19:54.200
And plutonium is
really interesting,

00:19:54.200 --> 00:19:55.575
he's explained a
bit of it to me.

00:19:55.575 --> 00:19:58.755
But here's what he wrote to
back up what I just said.

00:19:58.755 --> 00:20:01.430
"Our nuclear agreement
with North Korea

00:20:01.430 --> 00:20:05.000
was opposed immediately by
many in Congress who believed

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:07.220
that it rewarded bad behavior."

00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:10.010
if that sounds like what's
going on now with Iran,

00:20:10.010 --> 00:20:11.480
that's a good reason for it.

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:13.820
"Congress failed to
appropriate funds

00:20:13.820 --> 00:20:17.120
for key provisions of the
pact, causing the United States

00:20:17.120 --> 00:20:19.280
to fall behind in
its commitments

00:20:19.280 --> 00:20:20.870
almost from the beginning."

00:20:20.870 --> 00:20:23.030
You don't read about
that very much.

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:25.760
"In 2002, the Bush
administration

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:29.840
killed the agreed framework for
domestic political reasons."

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:32.000
End of quote from
Hecker's paper.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.130
But the end note has a
link to the entire paper,

00:20:34.130 --> 00:20:36.140
if you want to read it.

00:20:36.140 --> 00:20:37.760
So as I said, in
response, North Korea

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:40.820
kicked out the inspectors who
were guarding their plutonium

00:20:40.820 --> 00:20:43.160
stockpile, and they did
their first nuclear test

00:20:43.160 --> 00:20:45.290
four years later.

00:20:45.290 --> 00:20:47.270
Now, our book section
on North Korea

00:20:47.270 --> 00:20:50.450
goes further and explains why
North Korea would probably

00:20:50.450 --> 00:20:54.140
have over 100 nuclear
weapons today if it

00:20:54.140 --> 00:20:55.790
hadn't been for that agreement.

00:20:55.790 --> 00:20:59.420
Even though Bush abrogated
the agreement in 2002,

00:20:59.420 --> 00:21:01.190
it was enforced for
eight years, and it

00:21:01.190 --> 00:21:03.020
had some really
beneficial effects for us.

00:21:03.020 --> 00:21:05.990
Again, you don't read
about that in the media.

00:21:05.990 --> 00:21:10.070
And so the reason they'd have
probably 100 nuclear warheads

00:21:10.070 --> 00:21:15.740
or more, in 1994 when that
agreement went into effect,

00:21:15.740 --> 00:21:19.160
they were a year or two away
from completing a large nuclear

00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:21.770
reactor that would have
made enough plutonium--

00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:24.590
and very good
plutonium, by the way--

00:21:24.590 --> 00:21:27.570
enough plutonium for
about 10 bombs a year.

00:21:27.570 --> 00:21:30.530
So let's say it's finished in
1996, 21 years have elapsed.

00:21:30.530 --> 00:21:33.864
They'd have enough
plutonium for 210 warheads.

00:21:33.864 --> 00:21:35.780
Instead, they just have
a very small plutonium

00:21:35.780 --> 00:21:40.520
stockpile from a much smaller
reactor 1/10 the size of that.

00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:44.580
And in fact, not only did
they stop construction

00:21:44.580 --> 00:21:48.450
of that larger reactor
under the nuclear agreement

00:21:48.450 --> 00:21:50.490
that we had with
them, but it started

00:21:50.490 --> 00:21:53.280
to rust so badly from exposure
to the elements in the eight

00:21:53.280 --> 00:21:56.670
years that the agreement
was in force that--

00:21:56.670 --> 00:22:00.450
Hecker was there in
his last visit in 2010,

00:22:00.450 --> 00:22:03.120
he told me he saw cranes that
were having to dismantle it,

00:22:03.120 --> 00:22:04.494
because it was
going to fall down

00:22:04.494 --> 00:22:06.030
from exposure to the elements.

00:22:06.030 --> 00:22:09.780
And so when he gave
a guest lecture

00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:14.160
in a seminar around a
nuclear weapons risk and hope

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:16.500
at Stanford, on
North Korea he made

00:22:16.500 --> 00:22:18.720
a column A, what we got
from nuclear diplomacy

00:22:18.720 --> 00:22:23.160
with North Korea, and
column B, what they got.

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:24.750
And if you look at
the two columns,

00:22:24.750 --> 00:22:27.300
we got more from nuclear
diplomacy with North Korea

00:22:27.300 --> 00:22:28.440
than they did.

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:30.600
And again, that's very
contrary to the impression

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:33.140
you get from reading the media.

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:36.480
And so it's important to go
back and get at the facts

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:37.830
and avoid the fake news.

00:22:42.270 --> 00:22:46.380
So internationally, as
well as interpersonally,

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:51.540
it's often possible
for us to make progress

00:22:51.540 --> 00:22:54.000
on resolving a conflict when
it seems like the other side's

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:54.900
not interested.

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:57.316
I mean, that same thing happened
here in our relationship.

00:22:57.316 --> 00:22:59.634
So many times, I felt
like I was doing all--

00:22:59.634 --> 00:23:00.300
I mean, earlier.

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:03.840
Not the last 10,
15, even 20 years.

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:06.539
But 25 years ago, I
remember I was so mad at her

00:23:06.539 --> 00:23:08.580
at times, because I was
doing all this hard work.

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:11.730
I was committed to doing it, and
she wasn't doing a damn thing.

00:23:11.730 --> 00:23:13.800
Guess how she felt?

00:23:13.800 --> 00:23:14.910
The mirror image.

00:23:14.910 --> 00:23:16.790
It felt to her like she
was doing all of it,

00:23:16.790 --> 00:23:18.330
because you don't realize
when the other person is

00:23:18.330 --> 00:23:19.163
doing the hard work.

00:23:19.163 --> 00:23:21.300
They're just doing what
they should be doing.

00:23:21.300 --> 00:23:25.080
But the same is true
internationally in many cases.

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:29.280
There's another example of one
party to a conflict starting

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:31.560
a process of reconciliation.

00:23:31.560 --> 00:23:34.110
And this one is
particularly nice for here

00:23:34.110 --> 00:23:37.310
at Google, because it
involves cryptography.

00:23:37.310 --> 00:23:39.740
And it's also nice, because
I was one of the parties

00:23:39.740 --> 00:23:41.660
to the conflict,
but I wasn't the one

00:23:41.660 --> 00:23:43.760
who initiated the resolution.

00:23:43.760 --> 00:23:46.820
It was the director of NSA at
the time, Admiral Bobby Inman.

00:23:46.820 --> 00:23:48.800
This was 1978.

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:50.630
So as some of you know--

00:23:50.630 --> 00:23:52.820
but background for
the rest of you--

00:23:52.820 --> 00:23:56.186
in the 1970s, I was
at war with NSA.

00:23:56.186 --> 00:23:58.310
There were a number of
reasons, but I'll focus here

00:23:58.310 --> 00:24:01.850
on publishing my papers
on cryptography, including

00:24:01.850 --> 00:24:04.580
the one which was cited
in the Turing Award--

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:06.080
"New Directions
in Cryptography",

00:24:06.080 --> 00:24:09.110
which appeared in November 1976.

00:24:09.110 --> 00:24:16.610
NSA took the position that
research in cryptography

00:24:16.610 --> 00:24:20.120
was born classified,
meaning that even though I

00:24:20.120 --> 00:24:22.220
had no benefit of
classified information,

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:26.240
nor did Whit Diffie
in writing that paper,

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:29.630
the NSA had the right
to stop its publication.

00:24:29.630 --> 00:24:31.490
And I was in
violation of the law,

00:24:31.490 --> 00:24:34.070
and could be prosecuted
and even thrown in jail

00:24:34.070 --> 00:24:36.200
for publishing it in
international journals,

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:39.380
because it was then
being exported.

00:24:39.380 --> 00:24:40.370
Well, I fought back.

00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:45.200
I'm from the Bronx,
and I fought back.

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:47.870
Dorothie was very grateful when
it became big news, because she

00:24:47.870 --> 00:24:49.160
said, now if something
happens to you,

00:24:49.160 --> 00:24:50.480
there will be an investigation.

00:24:53.180 --> 00:24:54.440
But we never talked directly.

00:24:54.440 --> 00:24:56.870
We were fighting it
out in the press.

00:24:56.870 --> 00:24:59.780
And of course we
didn't get very far.

00:24:59.780 --> 00:25:03.140
Until 1978-- so several
years into the fight--

00:25:03.140 --> 00:25:05.300
I get a call at my
office at Stanford,

00:25:05.300 --> 00:25:08.000
and it's from the
director's office at NSA,

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:11.630
and they tell me that the
director Admiral Bobby Inman is

00:25:11.630 --> 00:25:13.610
going to be in California
in a couple of weeks,

00:25:13.610 --> 00:25:16.610
and would I be willing
to meet with him?

00:25:16.610 --> 00:25:18.124
Well, I jumped at
the opportunity.

00:25:18.124 --> 00:25:20.290
I mean, him and I were
fighting it out in the press.

00:25:20.290 --> 00:25:24.040
And a couple of weeks later,
Inman shows up at my office,

00:25:24.040 --> 00:25:27.010
and he told me that
he was meeting with me

00:25:27.010 --> 00:25:29.800
against the advice of all
the other senior people

00:25:29.800 --> 00:25:31.409
at the agency.

00:25:31.409 --> 00:25:32.950
And these are the
key words, he said,

00:25:32.950 --> 00:25:37.400
but I don't see the
harm in talking.

00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:39.590
Now, what's our position
with North Korea today?

00:25:39.590 --> 00:25:41.420
We're not going to talk to
them unless it's about their

00:25:41.420 --> 00:25:42.860
getting rid of their weapons.

00:25:42.860 --> 00:25:45.080
What's the harm in talking?

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:47.510
But coming back to Inman,
he told me another thing.

00:25:47.510 --> 00:25:49.220
He looked over at
me and he said,

00:25:49.220 --> 00:25:52.010
nice to see you
