DOROTHIE HELLMAN: And
the same principle

00:38:00.586 --> 00:38:03.810
is needed too to
get away from war.

00:38:03.810 --> 00:38:08.700
The same principles we need
to address global warming

00:38:08.700 --> 00:38:13.531
and all global issues.

00:38:13.531 --> 00:38:15.280
MARTIN HELLMAN: And
so we didn't have time

00:38:15.280 --> 00:38:17.350
to go into-- we talked
about compassion.

00:38:17.350 --> 00:38:21.250
The other approach to looking
at is holistic thinking.

00:38:21.250 --> 00:38:23.740
We had to seek solutions
that worked for both of us.

00:38:23.740 --> 00:38:25.660
We need as a nation
to seek solutions

00:38:25.660 --> 00:38:27.130
that work for the whole world.

00:38:27.130 --> 00:38:29.560
And just as we found
out that giving up

00:38:29.560 --> 00:38:31.540
what we thought we
wanted and seeking

00:38:31.540 --> 00:38:34.114
those holistic solutions
usually produced things

00:38:34.114 --> 00:38:36.280
that were better for me and
better for her than what

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:37.810
we thought we wanted
going into it,

00:38:37.810 --> 00:38:41.440
the same would be true for the
United States internationally.

00:38:41.440 --> 00:38:43.360
AUDIENCE: So I'm
trying to put together

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:46.500
the take home from this talk.

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:48.880
And I could sort of see
it with relationships,

00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:55.480
you know, assume my wife is
well-meaning and understanding

00:38:55.480 --> 00:38:58.750
and she wants the best and I
do, and we can work it out.

00:38:58.750 --> 00:39:02.950
But I'm having trouble with that
same idea with al-Qaeda, North

00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:04.385
Korea, et cetera.

00:39:07.600 --> 00:39:11.920
Are there people who are
evil and want our demise?

00:39:11.920 --> 00:39:14.620
Are you saying yes,
maybe there are,

00:39:14.620 --> 00:39:17.330
but we should talk to them
anyway, and it'll work out?

00:39:17.330 --> 00:39:19.870
But practically speaking,
what is the take

00:39:19.870 --> 00:39:23.560
home with difficult situations
where people don't have

00:39:23.560 --> 00:39:25.180
our best interest at heart.

00:39:25.180 --> 00:39:27.790
MARTIN HELLMAN: Good question.

00:39:27.790 --> 00:39:31.565
Well, we've already dealt with
North Korea, to some extent.

00:39:31.565 --> 00:39:33.523
AUDIENCE: All I've heard
is that we should talk

00:39:33.523 --> 00:39:35.200
to them, practically speaking.

00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:37.700
MARTIN HELLMAN: And we should
recognize mistakes we've made.

00:39:37.700 --> 00:39:40.780
Instead of accepting the--

00:39:40.780 --> 00:39:42.430
the societal belief
in America is

00:39:42.430 --> 00:39:44.232
that it's all North
Korea's fault.

00:39:44.232 --> 00:39:46.690
And if you read the North Korean
section of the book, which

00:39:46.690 --> 00:39:48.252
would take you
five to 10 minutes,

00:39:48.252 --> 00:39:50.210
you'll come away with a
very different picture.

00:39:50.210 --> 00:39:51.670
And then go to the
sources and see

00:39:51.670 --> 00:39:53.940
if I'm wrong about anything.

00:39:53.940 --> 00:39:56.170
But let's take al-Qaeda,
which is harder--

00:39:56.170 --> 00:39:59.350
I mean, to the
extent that al-Qaeda

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:01.720
seems largely responsible
for September 11, what

00:40:01.720 --> 00:40:04.240
a horrible, horrible thing.

00:40:04.240 --> 00:40:07.000
Well, it helps to try to
understand their perspective.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:08.500
You don't necessarily
agree with it.

00:40:08.500 --> 00:40:10.150
But it helps to understand
the perspective,

00:40:10.150 --> 00:40:12.608
and we'll be able to combat
them more effectively if we do,

00:40:12.608 --> 00:40:14.800
rather than just
demonizing them.

00:40:14.800 --> 00:40:19.240
Turns out, Osama bin Laden
felt that the United States

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:22.540
was responsible for 4 million
Muslim deaths, including

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:23.980
many children.

00:40:23.980 --> 00:40:27.730
He blames both us directly for
the Iraq war and the sanctions

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:32.470
that followed, but also
our support for Israel

00:40:32.470 --> 00:40:33.767
and how that has affected.

00:40:33.767 --> 00:40:35.350
He may be wrong on
the numbers, but he

00:40:35.350 --> 00:40:37.360
does have a legitimate
point there,

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:42.340
that we have not been adequately
concerned with Muslim deaths.

00:40:42.340 --> 00:40:44.680
And he then goes to an
eye for an eye and a tooth

00:40:44.680 --> 00:40:46.570
for a tooth, which
I disagree with.

00:40:46.570 --> 00:40:50.079
But if we would understand
instead of just demonizing him,

00:40:50.079 --> 00:40:52.120
if we would try to understand
where he came from,

00:40:52.120 --> 00:40:55.660
it might help us to realize
where we could pull back

00:40:55.660 --> 00:40:58.210
in the world, where we're
caught we're actually

00:40:58.210 --> 00:40:59.350
creating more jihadists.

00:41:02.260 --> 00:41:05.350
It's often said when we
have a drone strike that

00:41:05.350 --> 00:41:09.280
kills innocent civilians, you
may take out one jihadist,

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:10.600
but you create 10 more.

00:41:10.600 --> 00:41:12.140
We need to look at that.

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:13.515
DOROTHIE HELLMAN:
The other thing

00:41:13.515 --> 00:41:17.710
that we really don't consider is
that they really want to be OK.

00:41:17.710 --> 00:41:18.730
They want to survive.

00:41:18.730 --> 00:41:23.750
We've taken out a lot of
what we call bad actors.

00:41:23.750 --> 00:41:26.710
We've killed a lot of
leaders because they

00:41:26.710 --> 00:41:28.910
didn't follow our rules.

00:41:28.910 --> 00:41:33.640
And I think that if you
look at North Korea,

00:41:33.640 --> 00:41:37.270
they're not very happy
to be playing with us,

00:41:37.270 --> 00:41:40.736
because we don't play
by very good rules.

00:41:40.736 --> 00:41:42.610
And so I think you need
to consider that when

00:41:42.610 --> 00:41:44.859
you think that they're willing
to deal with us at all.

00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:52.600
Yeah, I think we
need to talk to them

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:56.590
and treat them as if they
have a right to do their thing

00:41:56.590 --> 00:41:57.512
their way.

00:41:57.512 --> 00:41:59.220
MARTIN HELLMAN: Not
here, but over there.

00:41:59.220 --> 00:42:01.042
DOROTHIE HELLMAN: Right.

00:42:01.042 --> 00:42:02.250
And I don't think we do that.

00:42:02.250 --> 00:42:04.560
Do you?

00:42:04.560 --> 00:42:06.360
MARTIN HELLMAN: Well,
one of the things

00:42:06.360 --> 00:42:09.030
we say in the book is we're
out for regime change in North

00:42:09.030 --> 00:42:09.840
Korea.

00:42:09.840 --> 00:42:11.754
I mean, we don't often
put it that bluntly,

00:42:11.754 --> 00:42:13.170
but if you think
about it, and you

00:42:13.170 --> 00:42:15.044
look at how we've done
regime change in Iraq,

00:42:15.044 --> 00:42:18.120
regime change in Libya, and
we're trying to do it in Syria,

00:42:18.120 --> 00:42:19.890
you can see where the
North Koreans would

00:42:19.890 --> 00:42:21.780
believe that we're out
for regime change there.

00:42:21.780 --> 00:42:23.610
And if you study it, you'll
see that we really want it,

00:42:23.610 --> 00:42:25.230
and the sanctions
are partly intended

00:42:25.230 --> 00:42:27.540
to cripple the regime
economically and produce

00:42:27.540 --> 00:42:28.890
a revolution.

00:42:28.890 --> 00:42:30.570
Now, regime change
in North Korea,

00:42:30.570 --> 00:42:32.737
let's imagine Kim Jong Un.

00:42:32.737 --> 00:42:35.070
What does regime change going
to mean for you personally

00:42:35.070 --> 00:42:37.520
in your life?

00:42:37.520 --> 00:42:39.140
You're going to die.

00:42:39.140 --> 00:42:41.090
So as long as we're
out for regime change,

00:42:41.090 --> 00:42:44.390
the only way you can counter
us is with nuclear weapons

00:42:44.390 --> 00:42:46.420
and ballistic missiles.

00:42:46.420 --> 00:42:48.460
Now, I don't like the
regime over there,

00:42:48.460 --> 00:42:49.900
but we have a decision to make.

00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:52.720
Are we going to give up on
regime change in North Korea

00:42:52.720 --> 00:42:54.971
and then have some hope of
reigning in their programs,

00:42:54.971 --> 00:42:57.345
or are we going to keep going
for regime change, in which

00:42:57.345 --> 00:42:59.140
case there's no
way they're going

00:42:59.140 --> 00:43:01.060
to give up their programs?

00:43:01.060 --> 00:43:03.310
And we made it
harder, by the way.

00:43:03.310 --> 00:43:06.100
And this is in the North
Korea section of the book.

00:43:06.100 --> 00:43:10.420
In 2003, Gaddafi gave up
his nuclear weapons program.

00:43:10.420 --> 00:43:13.204
President Bush, in a speech
that's on the State Department

00:43:13.204 --> 00:43:15.370
website-- so you don't have
to take my word for it--

00:43:15.370 --> 00:43:17.470
welcomed him into
the family of nations

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:20.410
and said his good
behavior will be rewarded.

00:43:20.410 --> 00:43:23.380
In 2011, when we helped
get the guy murdered,

00:43:23.380 --> 00:43:25.849
North Korea put out a press
release that said, yeah,

00:43:25.849 --> 00:43:26.890
we've learned our lesson.

00:43:26.890 --> 00:43:28.660
That's how you
reward good behavior.

00:43:28.660 --> 00:43:31.360
So it's not to
overlook the danger

00:43:31.360 --> 00:43:32.650
that these people post to us.

00:43:32.650 --> 00:43:34.090
It's not to become
some Pollyanna.

00:43:34.090 --> 00:43:37.240
But it's to start getting
beyond our fears, our anger,

00:43:37.240 --> 00:43:41.367
and our hatred, and dealing
with it more objectively.

00:43:41.367 --> 00:43:43.700
And by the way, the other
thing you have to worry about,

00:43:43.700 --> 00:43:45.320
this new map is not
going to take over

00:43:45.320 --> 00:43:46.640
the nation all at once.

00:43:46.640 --> 00:43:48.260
And so even if we
were Pollyannas,

00:43:48.260 --> 00:43:51.530
you wouldn't have to worry about
things changing immediately.

00:43:51.530 --> 00:43:53.690
And as it started
to gain traction,

00:43:53.690 --> 00:43:56.810
then you could see whether
we need to pull back.

00:43:56.810 --> 00:43:58.090
Another question in the back.

00:43:58.090 --> 00:44:00.970
AUDIENCE: How do you maintain
peace in your marriage now,

00:44:00.970 --> 00:44:03.430
and do you have a daily
or weekly practice that

00:44:03.430 --> 00:44:04.930
helps to maintain that?

00:44:04.930 --> 00:44:09.640
DOROTHIE HELLMAN: We practice
positive, unconditional regard.

00:44:09.640 --> 00:44:16.000
We know that the other person
has their best intent for us,

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:19.910
and we practice compassion.

00:44:19.910 --> 00:44:25.130
And we spend a lot of
time telling each other

00:44:25.130 --> 00:44:27.300
how much we love each other.

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:32.360
We spend little moments with
each other when we're away.

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:34.130
We call each other
and remind each other

00:44:34.130 --> 00:44:38.122
that we love each other, and
we're grateful for each other.

00:44:38.122 --> 00:44:39.160
Would you add anything?

00:44:39.160 --> 00:44:40.035
MARTIN HELLMAN: Yeah.

00:44:40.035 --> 00:44:43.150
So one of the short
takeaways in the book

00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:45.700
is get curious, not furious.

00:44:45.700 --> 00:44:48.250
It used to be when she did
things that I didn't like,

00:44:48.250 --> 00:44:49.930
I'd get angry at her.

00:44:49.930 --> 00:44:54.100
I'd yell at her, which
then started a cycle

00:44:54.100 --> 00:44:56.410
of psychological violence.

00:44:56.410 --> 00:44:59.046
Now, when she's doing something
that seems strange or crazy

00:44:59.046 --> 00:45:00.170
to me, I ask her questions.

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:02.470
And there's a story in
the book about a new car

00:45:02.470 --> 00:45:04.030
2 and 1/2 years ago.

00:45:04.030 --> 00:45:06.230
Our two cars at that
point were three years old

00:45:06.230 --> 00:45:08.260
and six years old,
and we typically

00:45:08.260 --> 00:45:10.850
keep the cars for 10, 15 years.

00:45:10.850 --> 00:45:14.980
And so this crazy woman
is looking at new cars.

00:45:14.980 --> 00:45:15.932
And the only thing--

00:45:15.932 --> 00:45:17.140
I mean, that's how it seemed.

00:45:17.140 --> 00:45:18.310
I mean, I knew she wasn't crazy.

00:45:18.310 --> 00:45:20.768
But I couldn't get past the
feeling that what she was doing

00:45:20.768 --> 00:45:22.600
was crazy.

00:45:22.600 --> 00:45:25.900
And so I went to her and
I said, what are you doing

00:45:25.900 --> 00:45:28.840
feels crazy to me, but
I know you're not crazy.

00:45:28.840 --> 00:45:30.140
What am I missing?

00:45:30.140 --> 00:45:32.410
I got curious
instead of furious.

00:45:32.410 --> 00:45:35.800
She then explained that a newer
car-- the three-year-old car

00:45:35.800 --> 00:45:37.660
had a backup camera
and blind spot

00:45:37.660 --> 00:45:40.480
detection that the
six-year-old car did not have.

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:43.540
Those safety features made her
much more comfortable driving.

00:45:43.540 --> 00:45:45.100
And the new car
she was looking at

00:45:45.100 --> 00:45:47.840
had even more safety features,
like collision avoidance

00:45:47.840 --> 00:45:49.670
for rear-end collision.

00:45:49.670 --> 00:45:53.950
And at our age, and especially
with the medication she's on,

00:45:53.950 --> 00:45:56.650
it would give her
more independence.

00:45:56.650 --> 00:45:58.240
All of a sudden,
what had seemed crazy

00:45:58.240 --> 00:46:01.900
was brilliant, not only
for her, but for me.

00:46:01.900 --> 00:46:04.270
It's made my driving a
lot more comfortable.

00:46:04.270 --> 00:46:06.700
In fact, every time we drive
that car on a road trip,

00:46:06.700 --> 00:46:11.030
I thank her for doing this
thing that seemed crazy to me.

00:46:11.030 --> 00:46:12.560
The other thing I'd add--

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:14.750
and it kind of relates
with what Dorothie said--

00:46:14.750 --> 00:46:18.350
every relationship has a
bank account of goodwill.

00:46:18.350 --> 00:46:20.404
When we first met and
we were madly in love,

00:46:20.404 --> 00:46:22.070
we got married nine
months after we met.

00:46:22.070 --> 00:46:23.510
You only took
seven, I know, Tim.

00:46:23.510 --> 00:46:26.360
But we were quickly
madly in love.

00:46:26.360 --> 00:46:27.920
The bank account
was overflowing.

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:31.070
Anything she wanted, I wanted
to do for her, and vice versa.

00:46:31.070 --> 00:46:33.710
But then life set in,
two kids, a mortgage,

00:46:33.710 --> 00:46:37.310
financial questions,
and the bank account

00:46:37.310 --> 00:46:39.470
went from positive
to zero, and was

00:46:39.470 --> 00:46:42.380
headed for what's called
marriage bankruptcy.

00:46:42.380 --> 00:46:46.860
And it took us years to
rebuild the bank account.

00:46:46.860 --> 00:46:49.610
But now the bank
account is so positive

00:46:49.610 --> 00:46:52.130
that we can have that
unconditional positive regard.

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:57.050
And a small thing that
feels like a slight wrong,

00:46:57.050 --> 00:46:58.700
like her looking at
the cars, does not

00:46:58.700 --> 00:47:02.640
become the big issue it
would have 30 years ago.

00:47:02.640 --> 00:47:05.950
AUDIENCE: With regard to
international issues--

00:47:05.950 --> 00:47:09.640
America, al-Qaeda, whatever--

00:47:09.640 --> 00:47:12.769
I'm wondering how these
principles can help there.

00:47:12.769 --> 00:47:14.560
Because at the end of
the day, you can only

00:47:14.560 --> 00:47:16.270
control your own actions.

00:47:16.270 --> 00:47:19.240
You can't really control
what al-Qaeda, whoever's

00:47:19.240 --> 00:47:23.080
on the other side, or maybe
even your spouse is going to do.

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:30.270
And I'm wondering what kind
of actual practical advice

00:47:30.270 --> 00:47:32.840
you might have that might
help the world become a better

00:47:32.840 --> 00:47:33.340
place.

00:47:33.340 --> 00:47:36.670
Because it's only we who
can control our actions,

00:47:36.670 --> 00:47:39.084
and we can't control
what other people do.

00:47:39.084 --> 00:47:40.750
MARTIN HELLMAN: There's
a story in there

00:47:40.750 --> 00:47:42.757
where I have this
epiphany, which relates

00:47:42.757 --> 00:47:43.840
very much to what you say.

00:47:43.840 --> 00:47:44.870
We had a huge fight.

00:47:44.870 --> 00:47:46.930
Must have been 30
years ago, maybe more.

00:47:46.930 --> 00:47:50.110
And I cool down enough to
think through, and I realized,

00:47:50.110 --> 00:47:52.000
now which would I
rather was true,

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:53.800
that my current
perception was correct,

00:47:53.800 --> 00:47:55.900
that was all this
crazy woman's fault--

00:47:55.900 --> 00:47:58.000
which is how I saw
her at that moment--

00:47:58.000 --> 00:47:59.980
in which case, I was
powerless to get out

00:47:59.980 --> 00:48:02.740
of the pain I was in,
or would I rather that I

00:48:02.740 --> 00:48:06.910
was missing something, and I
had played a part in this fight?

00:48:06.910 --> 00:48:10.390
In which case, I could apologize
for that, which would give me

00:48:10.390 --> 00:48:13.295
power to start a process
that might get me out

00:48:13.295 --> 00:48:14.170
of the pain I was in.

00:48:14.170 --> 00:48:16.750
With that motivation,
I found the role

00:48:16.750 --> 00:48:18.730
I had played in the fight,
I apologized to her,

00:48:18.730 --> 00:48:21.920
she apologized for what she had
done, and the argument ended.

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:23.020
And in the same way--

00:48:23.020 --> 00:48:26.150
I'm not saying al-Qaeda
will respond that way.

00:48:26.150 --> 00:48:30.010
But all we can do is look
for where we've made mistakes

00:48:30.010 --> 00:48:31.070
and correct those.

00:48:31.070 --> 00:48:33.490
And fortunately, there
are a huge number

00:48:33.490 --> 00:48:37.000
of mistakes that we've made as
a nation that we could correct.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:38.560
I also would recommend
that we don't

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:43.807
start with al-Qaeda or with the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict.

00:48:43.807 --> 00:48:45.265
In fact, we had a
section on Israel

00:48:45.265 --> 00:48:47.620
in an early draft of
the book that we pulled.

00:48:47.620 --> 00:48:49.350
AUDIENCE: No, I
totally buy all this.

00:48:49.350 --> 00:48:52.240
I'm just wondering from a
practical standpoint how much--

00:48:52.240 --> 00:48:54.530
MARTIN HELLMAN:
Practical standpoint?

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:57.580
Well, we also should go
for the low-hanging fruit.

00:48:57.580 --> 00:49:00.670
So just like Israel-Palestine
is not the low hanging fruit,

00:49:00.670 --> 00:49:03.400
Russia-US is the
low-hanging fruit.

00:49:03.400 --> 00:49:07.060
What conflicts do we
have with Russia, really?

00:49:07.060 --> 00:49:08.050
Ukraine?

00:49:08.050 --> 00:49:09.490
Not that big a deal.

00:49:09.490 --> 00:49:10.948
DOROTHIE HELLMAN:
So maybe you need

00:49:10.948 --> 00:49:13.696
to talk to your congressman
and those kinds of things.

00:49:13.696 --> 00:49:15.070
MARTIN HELLMAN:
Oh, you're asking

00:49:15.070 --> 00:49:16.455
what can we do as individuals?

00:49:16.455 --> 00:49:17.080
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:49:17.080 --> 00:49:19.059
MARTIN HELLMAN: Oh,
a couple of things.

00:49:19.059 --> 00:49:21.100
First of all, the most
effective thing you can do

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:24.100
is to bring greater
and greater peace

00:49:24.100 --> 00:49:27.790
to your personal relationships,
because that will motivate

00:49:27.790 --> 00:49:29.980
you to continue
the process, and it

00:49:29.980 --> 00:49:31.570
will make you a
convincing advocate

00:49:31.570 --> 00:49:33.310
for these seemingly
impossible changes

00:49:33.310 --> 00:49:34.480
at the international level.

00:49:38.774 --> 00:49:40.690
If you really want to
play a role, contact us,

00:49:40.690 --> 00:49:43.780
we'll talk through our
email address on the cards.

00:49:43.780 --> 00:49:48.310
And we'd love to talk with you
about what role you might play.

00:49:48.310 --> 00:49:51.760
I contribute to a number of
congressional candidates.

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:54.940
And the way I choose them
is when they call me--

00:49:54.940 --> 00:49:58.530
and once you give to a few, a
whole bunch start calling you.

00:49:58.530 --> 00:49:59.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:59.760 --> 00:50:02.500
I have this huge
target painted on me.

00:50:02.500 --> 00:50:05.710
I always discuss with them these
issues, North Korea, Russia,

00:50:05.710 --> 00:50:08.440
and whether they're
interested in informing a more

00:50:08.440 --> 00:50:11.260
objective based foreign
policy, instead of based

00:50:11.260 --> 00:50:13.861
on the demonization of Russia
that we have, and so on.

00:50:13.861 --> 00:50:15.610
And I'm actually working
with some of them

00:50:15.610 --> 00:50:17.920
to see whether we might
get that information out

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:20.689
to other people within Congress.

00:50:20.689 --> 00:50:22.480
But if you don't give
money to congressmen,

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:24.670
you can always write
letters to your congressmen,

00:50:24.670 --> 00:50:25.602
your senators.

00:50:25.602 --> 00:50:27.310
And you might wonder
living in California

00:50:27.310 --> 00:50:28.780
what difference that makes.

00:50:28.780 --> 00:50:31.690
Because for example
Senator Feinstein

00:50:31.690 --> 00:50:34.360
is going to vote the
way I would want her to

00:50:34.360 --> 00:50:35.950
on most of these issues.

00:50:35.950 --> 00:50:38.530
But someone pointed out to me
who really knows how Washington

00:50:38.530 --> 00:50:42.160
works that lobbying Feinstein is
very important on these issues,

00:50:42.160 --> 00:50:45.670
because she has great
political capital in DC.

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:48.340
People on both sides of
the aisle respect her.

00:50:48.340 --> 00:50:50.590
But how she spends
that political capital

00:50:50.590 --> 00:50:53.010
depends on what she
sees as important.

00:50:53.010 --> 00:50:59.500
And getting her to move
these issues up in her agenda

00:50:59.500 --> 00:51:01.000
will cause her to do more.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:04.540
DOROTHIE HELLMAN: There is one
other thing that's important.

00:51:04.540 --> 00:51:06.880
We don't know how these
changes are going to occur.

00:51:06.880 --> 00:51:09.670
Just like in 1900,
we didn't know

00:51:09.670 --> 00:51:13.240
how we were going to get
to women voting in 1920.

00:51:13.240 --> 00:51:16.450
But we knew that the more
people talked about this,

00:51:16.450 --> 00:51:20.410
the more they acted on
it, the more it spread.

00:51:20.410 --> 00:51:21.910
It was going to happen.

00:51:21.910 --> 00:51:25.540
So we don't know the magic
that happens out there

00:51:25.540 --> 00:51:27.580
to get something
like this started.

00:51:27.580 --> 00:51:30.610
All we know is that
we can do our part.

00:51:30.610 --> 00:51:33.460
We can talk to people about it.

00:51:33.460 --> 00:51:35.720
We can behave it.

00:51:35.720 --> 00:51:37.490
We can do what we can.

00:51:37.490 --> 00:51:41.240
But we can't see from
here to there to know.

00:51:41.240 --> 00:51:42.674
We can only do our part.

00:51:42.674 --> 00:51:44.840
Get a group of friends
together to all read the book

00:51:44.840 --> 00:51:47.350
and discuss each chapter and
then tear it apart, and see

00:51:47.350 --> 00:51:48.600
whether you agree or disagree.

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:50.270
That creates a small group.

00:51:50.270 --> 00:51:52.010
But that's how all
these things work.

00:51:52.010 --> 00:51:54.500
ANDRE: Thank you very
much, Martin and Dorothie,

00:51:54.500 --> 00:51:55.040
for coming.

00:51:55.040 --> 00:51:56.930
And let's give them
a round of applause.

00:51:56.930 --> 00:52:00.280
[APPLAUSE]

